         <abstract>
            <p>J. M. Pollard, in 1974, presented the $P - 1$ integer factoring algorithm. His paper couched the algorithm in theoretical terms based upon use of Fast Fourier Transform techniques, but he was unable to say whether the method could be made practical. We discuss the mathematical basis of the algorithm and show how it can work in practice. The practical implementation depends, for its success, upon the use of Residue Number Systems. We also present an open problem as to how the method could be made to work for the Elliptic Curve factoring algorithm.</p>
          </abstract>
